The Telegraph - Calcutta : Nation

NATION BRIEFS

 Chennai, April 23 (PTI): Security has been beefed up near ADMK chief Jayalalithaas residence after an anonymous letter threatening to kill the former chief minister was received yesterday. Police said the letter, received at the office of Jaya TV, asked the channel to stop its criticism against chief minister M. Karunanidhi.

 An official of the channel has lodged a complaint with Chennai police commissioner Letika Saran.

 Kuala Lumpur (PTI): Malaysia is set to enforce visa rules more strictly after it found that many tourists, including Indians, were overstaying by misusing the visa-on-arrival scheme launched last year. 

 Cuddalore (PTI): A group of people suspected to be Dravidar Kazhagam volunteers, entered a temple in Neyveli with knives and allegedly cut off the sacred thread of an 80-year-old priest. Before fleeing, the group also allegedly damaged an idol. One person has been arrested.

 Varanasi (PTI): The wife of a slain Naxalite and another rebel have been arrested from the area in Uttar Pradesh while trying to flee to Bihar, police said. The duo, carrying a reward of Rs 10,000 on their heads, was involved in at least 15 cases of murder and loot.

 Chandigarh (PTI): The Haryana government has decided not to charge tuition fees from girl students of Class I to XII in government schools in an effort to promote girls education in the state.

 The picture in Mondays The Buzz in Big Cities on page 4 was that of a male purple sunbird, not hummingbird as mentioned in the caption. Besides, the bird was sucking nectar, not honey. We apologise for the errors.




